File: platform/cli/src/commands/config.ts, around line 56-58. The --json branch currently does:
```
const output = { ...config, ...(displaySecret ? { secret: displaySecret } : {}) };
console.log(JSON.stringify(output, null, 2));
```
When both --json and --show-secret are true, also build an 'mcpClients' object. The MCP client config data is already structured in start.ts printMcpClientConfigs (line 164-195). To avoid duplication, extract the config data structure (the array of { label, file, json }) into a shared helper function that both start.ts and config.ts can use. The helper should be in start.ts (or a new shared file) and exported. It takes (mcpUrl, secret) and returns the array of config objects. Then config.ts can import it and include the data in the JSON output. The port comes from config.port (line 167 in config.ts).
